% You are an expert Python engineer. Generate the module `pdd/codex_subscription.py`.

% Purpose
Provide ChatGPT/Codex **subscription** support for PDD's inner `llm_invoke` path
(issue #1269). The subscription is reached through litellm's `chatgpt/` provider,
which calls `https://chatgpt.com/backend-api/codex` using the OAuth token the
`codex` CLI writes on `codex login` (ChatGPT sign-in). Per issue #1318 this is now
the **default** flat-rate route for `pdd sync` and every `llm_invoke` caller —
preferred ahead of Anthropic API-key models — and it also serves when no other
provider is usable (e.g. `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` missing or rate-limited), fixing the
`--force` failure class in #1254 / #1135. Anthropic API-key paths remain available
only as an explicit opt-in.

Bring-your-own-subscription only: each user authenticates their own ChatGPT
account; never pool or share one subscription across users.

% Module constants
- `CHATGPT_MODEL_PREFIX = "chatgpt/"` — litellm routes any model with this prefix
  through the subscription backend.
- `_TOKEN_FIELDS = ("access_token", "refresh_token", "id_token", "account_id")` —
  the OAuth fields litellm's ChatGPT authenticator consumes from `auth.json`.

% Auth-shape reconciliation
The `codex` CLI stores its token at `$CODEX_HOME/auth.json` (default
`~/.codex/auth.json`) with the OAuth fields **nested** under a `"tokens"` object,
while litellm's authenticator reads `$CHATGPT_TOKEN_DIR/auth.json` (default
`~/.config/litellm/chatgpt`) and expects them at the **top level**. The bridge
flattens the former into the latter so a user (or the cloud worker) supplies the
codex `auth.json` once.

% Public functions
- `is_chatgpt_subscription_model(model_name) -> bool`: True when the model name
  starts with `chatgpt/` (case-insensitive; tolerate None).
- `bridge_codex_auth_for_litellm() -> bool`: idempotent, best-effort, never
  raises. Returns True when a usable token is staged.
  1. If `CHATGPT_TOKEN_DIR` points at a directory OTHER than PDD's own bridged
     dir and it holds a usable `auth.json`, respect it untouched.
  2. Otherwise read `$CODEX_HOME/auth.json` (honor `CODEX_HOME`; default
     `~/.codex`), flatten the nested `tokens` to top level, and write it 0600 in
     a 0700 private dir (`PDD_CHATGPT_TOKEN_DIR` override, else
     `~/.cache/pdd/chatgpt`), exporting `CHATGPT_TOKEN_DIR` to that dir.
  3. When there is no *usable* `$CODEX_HOME/auth.json` — absent, OR present but
     malformed / unreadable / missing an `access_token` — but `CODEX_API_KEY` is
     set non-empty, stage its value as the top-level `access_token` in that same
     private dir (issue #1318 — a ChatGPT OAuth access token injected directly for
     headless/CI, e.g. a cloud worker; NOT an OpenAI `sk-` API key), exporting
     `CHATGPT_TOKEN_DIR`, so the `chatgpt/` route can authenticate without a
     logged-in `auth.json`. Precedence: a usable `auth.json` (rotation-aware) wins,
     then `CODEX_API_KEY`, then a previously-staged usable copy. A
     malformed/unreadable `auth.json` MUST NOT short-circuit the bridge — neither to
     failure NOR to a stale previously-staged copy — while a non-empty `CODEX_API_KEY`
     is set; the freshly-injected env token is (re)staged instead, so a rotated key
     always wins over a stale staged copy. INVARIANT: this must stay consistent with
     `has_codex_subscription_auth()` (which treats a non-empty `CODEX_API_KEY` as
     usable) — whenever detection reports a usable subscription, the bridge must be
     able to stage a usable token; never return `has=True` with `bridge=False`.
  Refresh the bridged copy only when the codex source is newer (rotation-aware),
  so a long-running worker picks up `codex`-rotated tokens.
- `has_codex_subscription_auth() -> bool`: True when a usable subscription token
  exists (explicit `CHATGPT_TOKEN_DIR` first, then a non-empty `CODEX_API_KEY`
  env var, then `$CODEX_HOME/auth.json`). Issue #1318: `CODEX_API_KEY` is accepted
  as a valid subscription credential signal so headless/cloud environments that
  inject the ChatGPT OAuth access token via env (the `CODEX_API_KEY` value is that
  access token — NOT an OpenAI `sk-` API key — rather than a logged-in `auth.json`)
  are still recognized as having a usable subscription. Used by the credential check so a
  `chatgpt/` model is skipped cleanly in `PDD_FORCE` mode instead of hanging
  litellm on an interactive device login, AND by `llm_invoke`'s default-routing
  guard (Issue #1318) to decide whether the default candidate universe should be
  the `chatgpt/*` subscription family instead of Anthropic API-key rows.
- `apply_litellm_chatgpt_output_patch() -> bool`: work around litellm returning
  empty output for `chatgpt/` non-streaming Responses (upstream
  BerriAI/litellm#25429). The Codex backend streams content via
  `response.output_item.done` SSE events and an empty `response.completed.output`;
  litellm's non-stream parser misses it. Wrap
  `ChatGPTResponsesAPIConfig.transform_response_api_response` to splice the
  collected `output_item.done` items into the completed event before delegating
  to litellm's own (version-correct) transform. Idempotent, version-gated, never
  raises; no-op if the class/method is absent.
- `build_chatgpt_schema_instruction(schema) -> str`: the subscription backend
  ignores `response_format`/`json_schema`, so return a prompt instruction that
  coerces a single JSON object matching `schema` (no prose, no fences), injected
  in-band by `llm_invoke` (mirrors the Groq handling). This same constraint means
  `llm_invoke` must NOT send `response_format` for `chatgpt/` models on the
  initial call OR on any retry/repair path.

% Helpers (private)
`_codex_home`, `_codex_auth_path`, `_flatten_codex_tokens` (accept nested or
already-flat; return None without a usable `access_token`), `_bridged_token_dir`,
`_write_private_json` (0700 dir / 0600 file). A `_RawResponseProxy` wraps an
httpx-style response overriding only `.text` for the output patch.

% Constraints
- Standard library + litellm only. Never raise into callers — every public
  function degrades to "subscription unavailable" on error and logs at debug.
- Do not import `pdd.llm_invoke` (avoid a cycle); `llm_invoke` imports this.
